\begin{abstract}
Clinical AI systems are overwhelmingly benchmarked in English, yet a billion-plus speakers of Indian languages rely on healthcare systems
where consultations happens in diverse regional languages. We study whether current open-source LLMs can generate
trustworthy English clinical summaries directly from multilingual doctor-patient dialogues, a practically important setting that has received almost no systematic attention. We evaluate two 7B-parameter LLMs (Mistral-7B and Qwen2.5-7B) across ten typologically diverse Indian languages under four conditions: zero-shot prompting, few-shot prompting ($k{=}1$), translation of
source dialogues to English via IndicTrans2 before summarization, and LoRA-based supervised fine-tuning.

We find that few-shot
prompting \emph{degrades} performance
in 16 of 20 language--model pairs; translation helps Indo-Aryan but
harms Dravidian languages; and clinical Safety scores remain below 3.0/5.0 across every condition. Fine-tuning eliminates the cross-lingual performance gap, post-SFT Dravidian F1 reaches parity with English, while reducing macro-average hallucination from $\sim$42\% to $\sim$10\%. We additionally conduct systematic qualitative case analysis across all ten languages, yielding an eight-category
Clinical Error Taxonomy that characterizes failure modes by method and language family.
