%\paragraph{Zero-shot (ZS).}
\noindent\textbf{Zero-shot (ZS).}
The model receives a prompt instructing it to generate a structured English clinical summary covering chief complaint, symptoms,
investigations, treatment, and follow-up, without introducing unsupported medical claims. The prompt and source dialogue
are the only inputs. This is the primary baseline.

%\paragraph{Few-Shot (FS).}
\noindent\textbf{Few-Shot (FS).}
Few-shot prompting augments the zero-shot prompt with a small number of demonstration examples, $k = 1$ in our case, drawn from the training set. Each example consists of: a doctor–patient dialogue, and its corresponding gold English summary. Few-shot prompting is applied uniformly across all three models to enable a fair comparison. The objective is to condition the model on the desired output format and clinical content structure, thereby reducing the ambiguity inherent in open-ended summarization tasks.

%\paragraph{Translation (Trans).}
\noindent\textbf{Translation (Trans).}
A well-established strategy for low-resource NLP is translate-then-summarize: translate the source text into a high-resource language, and apply the NLP pipeline in that language. Given the strong English summarization capabilities of both target models, we explore whether routing non-English dialogues through a high-quality neural machine translation (NMT) system before summarization yields improvements over direct multilingual inference.
Non-English source dialogues are first translated to English using IndicTrans2~\citep{gala2023indictrans2}, then summarized under the same zero-shot English prompt. Since the target output is an English
summary. The translated English dialogue replaces the source dialogue; everything downstream is identical to zero-shot. The hypothesis is that routing through English allows models to summarize in their strongest generation language, compensating for weaker multilingual generation calibration.

%\paragraph{Supervised Fine-Tuning (SFT).}
\noindent\textbf{Supervised Fine-Tuning (SFT).}
We fine-tune both the \texttt{Mistral-7B-Instruct} and \texttt{Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct} models using Low-Rank Adaptation (LoRA) on the full multilingual training set. For \texttt{Qwen2.5-7B}, we employ a rank $r=8$, $\alpha=32$, and dropout $0.05$, targeting the \texttt{q\_proj}, \texttt{k\_proj}, \texttt{v\_proj}, \texttt{o\_proj}, \texttt{gate\_proj}, \texttt{up\_proj}, and \texttt{down\_proj} layers. Both models are trained using 4-bit NormalFloat (NF4) quantization. Training is conducted for $3$ epochs using the AdamW optimizer with a learning rate of $2 \times 10^{-5}$ and a per-device batch size of $1$. We use gradient accumulation with $8$ steps to achieve an effective batch size of $8$. To optimize memory, we enable gradient checkpointing and use the \texttt{expandable\_segments} configuration for the CUDA memory allocator. At inference, models utilize the same chat templates and clinical prompting constraints as established in the zero-shot experiments.

\subsection{Evaluation Framework}
We employ a three-tier evaluation framework designed to assess the quality of generated clinical summaries from complementary perspectives: Surface-level lexical similarity, Holistic quality dimensions via LLM-as-a-judge, and Clinical entity-level analysis.
%\begin{itemize}
