\subsection{Qwen2.5-7B Outperforms Mistral-7B, Mainly at Zero-Shot}

At zero-shot, Qwen2.5-7B leads Mistral-7B on every entity-level
metric: F1 0.518 vs.\ 0.432 ($+$0.086), precision 0.576 vs.\ 0.490,
recall 0.484 vs.\ 0.392, hallucination 0.424 vs.\ 0.510.
Qwen also leads on LLM-judge dimensions: Truthfulness by 0.226,
Explainability by 0.336. The one exception is ROUGE-L, where Mistral
is marginally higher (0.1352 vs.\ 0.1318), but this reflects shorter,
more formulaic outputs that happen to share surface n-grams with gold
summarie, not better clinical coverage, as confirmed by lower entity
F1 and BERTScore. Qwen's advantage traces to its broader multilingual
pretraining: its token representations for non-Latin scripts are
better calibrated, giving it stronger generative confidence in
Dravidian and low-resource Indo-Aryan languages.

After fine-tuning, the gap narrows substantially: 0.775 vs.\ 0.760
F1 ($+$0.014). The remaining difference is small and probably reflects
model-specific capacity for clinical summarization rather than
language-family effects. Practitioners working in resource-constrained
settings should prefer Qwen2.5-7B for prompting-based deployment;
for fine-tuned deployment, both models are viable.

\subsection{Safety Is the Hardest Dimension to Improve}

Safety is the lowest-scoring dimension in every single experimental
condition for both models, and it is the only dimension that fails
to reach 3.0/5.0 even after fine-tuning. The scores range from
1.42 (Mistral-Assamese translation) to 3.08 (Qwen-Kannada SFT),
with macro-averages between 2.197 and 2.962. Looking at the
safety-truthfulness gap by condition:

